{
  "topicId": "vanishing-points",
  "flashcards": [
    {
      "id": "fc-1",
      "front": "Define Vanishing Point in computer graphics.",
      "back": "A vanishing point is a point on the image plane where parallel lines in a 3D scene appear to converge or meet when projected using perspective projection. It creates the illusion of depth and distance in a 2D representation, mimicking human visual perception."
    },
    {
      "id": "fc-2",
      "front": "What is 1-point perspective and when is it used?",
      "back": "1-point perspective uses a single vanishing point on the horizon line, where all lines perpendicular to the viewer's line of sight converge. It is ideal for scenes looking directly at the front of an object, such as hallways, railroad tracks, or interior room views."
    },
    {
      "id": "fc-3",
      "front": "Explain 2-point perspective with its configuration.",
      "back": "2-point perspective uses two vanishing points on the horizon line, typically placed at left and right extremes. Vertical lines remain parallel while horizontal lines converge to their respective vanishing points. It is commonly used for drawing buildings, objects viewed from a corner, and architectural illustrations."
    },
    {
      "id": "fc-4",
      "front": "What is 3-point perspective and what is its primary application?",
      "back": "3-point perspective employs three vanishing points: two on the horizon line and a third placed either above (for bird's eye view) or below (for worm's eye view) the horizon. It is used for rendering tall structures like skyscrapers or for dramatic aerial/ground-level perspectives to emphasize height or scale."
    },
    {
      "id": "fc-5",
      "front": "What is the mathematical formula for perspective projection to a vanishing point?",
      "back": "For a point P(x, y, z) and camera at origin looking down -Z axis, the perspective projection is: x' = x * (d/z), y' = y * (d/z), where d is the focal length (distance from camera to projection plane). The vanishing point for parallel lines along an axis occurs at z = infinity, making x' = 0, y' = 0."
    },
